with a 5-minute gap, and assert returned conflict intervals and implicated run pairs match expected windows.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.32,"Integration":0.63,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Timezone-aware scheduling is correct across DST spring-forward and fall-back around 2:30 AM.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on real timezone/DST rules from the runtime tz database, which is effectively OS/runtime infrastructure. In-process mocks of timezone behavior can trivially pass while masking real transition bugs.","test_description":"Run with real timezone data (e.g., `America/New_York`). For known DST dates, compute next runs for `2:30 AM` schedule and assert behavior for nonexistent spring-forward time and duplicated fall-back hour matches product rules.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.65,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Engine applies missed-run policy (skip vs backfill) when computed next run is in the past.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior usually spans schedule computation, current-time evaluation, and policy/state handling. Unit tests of policy logic alone can miss defects in how engine wiring determines 'missed' runs after downtime.","test_description":"Using real engine components (clock input, schedule calc, policy config, job state), simulate downtime so next run is past due. Assert `skip` policy advances to future run without enqueueing missed runs, while `backfill` enqueues expected missed executions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
